### OAuth2 Pushed Authorization Request (PAR) Authorization Code Flow
# Goal:
# 1) Discover the PAR endpoint from server metadata.
# 2) Push the authorization request directly to the auth server.
# 3) Receive a short-lived `request_uri`.
# 4) Open the normal authorization endpoint in a browser using `request_uri`.
# 5) Copy the authorization code from the browser redirect URL.
# 6) Exchange the code for tokens using the same PKCE verifier.
#
# Why this matters:
# PAR moves the authorization request parameters off the front channel.
# Instead of sending the full request through the browser as query parameters,
# the client pushes the request directly to the authorization server and only
# sends `client_id` + `request_uri` through the browser.
#
# Prerequisites:
# 1) Start auth server: ./mvnw -pl oauth/auth-server spring-boot:run
# 2) This walkthrough uses the confidential client registered as:
#    client_id=quotes, client_secret=abc123
# 3) The browser step will redirect to http://127.0.0.1:8080/ after login.
#    You do not need a web app running on port 8080 for this walkthrough.
#    If nothing is listening there, the browser will fail to load the page,
#    but the address bar will still contain the authorization code to copy.
#
# Notes:
# 1) This auth server expects PKCE on these authorization requests.
# 2) The fixed verifier/challenge pair below is used to keep the walkthrough manual.

@authServer = http://localhost:9090
@client_id = quotes
@client_secret = abc123
@redirect_uri = http://127.0.0.1:8080/
@scope = openid%20quotes.read
@state = par-demo-state
@code_verifier = par-demo-verifier-1234567890abcdef-uvwxyz-ABCDEFG
@code_challenge = hwq_-lWhFiLSDMutcBeY2t7ftUkYI-clmfYqW2kHjCE

### Step 1: Fetch OIDC discovery metadata.
### Confirm that `pushed_authorization_request_endpoint` is present.
GET {{authServer}}/.well-known/openid-configuration
Accept: application/json

> {%
  const parEndpoint = response.body.pushed_authorization_request_endpoint;
  if (!parEndpoint) {
    throw new Error("Server metadata did not advertise pushed_authorization_request_endpoint");
  }
  client.global.set("par_endpoint", parEndpoint);
%}

###

### Step 2: Push the authorization request to the PAR endpoint.
### Expected result: HTTP 201 with `request_uri` and `expires_in`.
POST {{par_endpoint}}
Authorization: Basic {{client_id}} {{client_secret}}
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Accept: application/json

response_type=code&client_id={{client_id}}&redirect_uri={{redirect_uri}}&scope={{scope}}&state={{state}}&code_challenge={{code_challenge}}&code_challenge_method=S256

> {%
  if (!response.body.request_uri) {
    throw new Error("PAR response did not contain request_uri");
  }
  client.global.set("request_uri", response.body.request_uri);

  const authorizationUrl =
      "http://localhost:9090/oauth2/authorize?client_id=quotes&request_uri="
      + encodeURIComponent(response.body.request_uri);

  client.global.set("authorization_url", authorizationUrl);
  client.log("Open this URL in a browser:");
  client.log(authorizationUrl);
%}

###

### Step 3: Open the authorization URL printed in the console after Step 2.
### The same URL is also available as:
### {{authorization_url}}
###
### Then:
### 1) Log in with user/user
### 2) Approve consent if prompted
### 3) After redirect, copy the `code` query parameter from the browser address bar
### 4) Paste that value into `@authorization_code` at the top of this file
### 5) If something is already running on port 8080, the page may still render normally.
###    That is fine. The important part is the `?code=...` value in the browser URL.

###

### Step 4: Exchange the authorization code for tokens.
### This must use the same redirect_uri and PKCE code_verifier as the pushed request.
### Do not run this step until you replace `@authorization_code` with the real code from Step 3.

# After Step 3, copy only the value of the `code` query parameter from the browser URL.
# Example browser URL:
# http://127.0.0.1:8080/?code=abc123xyz&state=par-demo-state
# Example value to paste below:
# abc123xyz
@authorization_code = COPY-PASTE-AUTH-CODE

POST {{authServer}}/oauth2/token
Authorization: Basic {{client_id}} {{client_secret}}
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Accept: application/json

grant_type=authorization_code&code={{authorization_code}}&redirect_uri={{redirect_uri}}&code_verifier={{code_verifier}}

> {%
  if (response.body.access_token) {
    client.global.set("access_token", response.body.access_token);
  }
%}

###

### Step 5: Call the OIDC UserInfo endpoint with the issued access token.
GET {{authServer}}/userinfo
Authorization: Bearer {{access_token}}
Accept: application/json

###

### Step 6 (optional): Start the `quotes-protected-resource` sample if you want
### to use the same access token against a resource server endpoint.
### Run:
### ./mvnw -pl oauth/quotes-protected-resource spring-boot:run
###
### That sample runs on http://127.0.0.1:8081 and exposes `/whoami`.
GET http://127.0.0.1:8081/whoami
Authorization: Bearer {{access_token}}
Accept: application/json
